<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:237px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Healthywealthy.jpg" class="image" title="The Three Stooges' comedy trademark was exaggerated slapstick routines where a performer's apparent pain created enjoyment and laughter among their audience."><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/a/ae/Healthywealthy.jpg/235px-Healthywealthy.jpg" width="235" height="169" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Healthywealthy.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/The_Three_Stooges" title="The Three Stooges">The Three Stooges</a>' comedy trademark was exaggerated slapstick routines where a performer's apparent pain created enjoyment and laughter among their audience.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p><b>Schadenfreude</b> (<small>IPA</small>:&#160;<span title="Pronunciation in IPA" class="IPA"><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:IPA" title="Wikipedia:IPA">[ˈʃaːdənˌfʁɔʏ̯də]</a></span> <span class="unicode" style="white-space:nowrap;"><a href="/wiki/File:De-schadenfreude.ogg" title="File:De-schadenfreude.ogg"><img alt="De-schadenfreude.ogg" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Loudspeaker.svg/11px-Loudspeaker.svg.png" width="11" height="11" border="0" /></a> <a href="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/03/De-schadenfreude.ogg" class="internal" title="De-schadenfreude.ogg">Audio (German)</a> <small class="metadata audiolinkinfo">(<a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Media_help" title="Wikipedia:Media help">help</a>·<a href="/wiki/File:De-schadenfreude.ogg" title="File:De-schadenfreude.ogg">info</a>)</small></span>) is pleasure derived from the misfortunes of others. The word referring to this emotion has been borrowed from German by the English language<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> and is sometimes also used as a <a href="/wiki/Loanword" title="Loanword">loanword</a> by other languages.</p>
<p><a href="/wiki/Philosopher" title="Philosopher" class="mw-redirect">Philosopher</a> and <a href="/wiki/Sociologist" title="Sociologist" class="mw-redirect">sociologist</a> <a href="/wiki/Theodor_Adorno" title="Theodor Adorno" class="mw-redirect">Theodor Adorno</a> defined schadenfreude as “largely unanticipated delight in the suffering of another which is cognized as trivial and/or appropriate.”<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
